Turkish Stocks: Garanti, Sabanci, Petkim, Sekerbank Are Active

-- B y   B e n j a m i n   H a r v e y
-- 
2011-09-28T15:27:09Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-09-28/arcelik-petkim-petrol-ofisi-yapi-kredi-turkey-stocks-preview.html
Turkey ’s benchmark  ISE National 100
Index (XU100)  rose for a third day, climbing 727.19, or 1.3 percent, to
58,988.46 at the 5:30 p.m. close in Istanbul.  The following stocks were active. Symbols are in
parentheses.  Haci Omer Sabanci Holding AS (SAHOL)  , Turkey’s second
biggest group of companies, increased 22 kurus, or 3.5 percent,
to 6.48 liras, the biggest gain in more than a week. Turkey’s
state-asset sales agency may offer the  power grid  on the Asian
side of Istanbul to Enerjisa Enerji Uretim AS, the power company
jointly owned by Sabanci and Austria’s Verbund AG, Vatan
newspaper reported today.  Petkim Petrokimya Holding AS (PETKM)  , Turkey’s biggest
chemicals maker, gained 4 kurus, or 1.7 percent, to 2.41 liras,
its highest since Aug. 16. Petkim will sell its air separation
unit for $39 million and lease the land on which it stands to
Air Liquide SA’s Turkish unit by Sept. 30, the company said in a
statement after the market closed yesterday.  Sekerbank TAS (SKBNK)  , a Turkish bank part-owned by
Kazakhstan’s BTA Bank JSC, rose 3 kurus, or 3.3 percent, to 93
kurus, advancing for a second day. BTA is seeking a buyer for
its 34 percent stake, according to a report in the Wall Street
Journal.  Turkiye Garanti Bankasi AS (GARAN)  , Turkey’s largest
bank by market value, gained 18 kurus, or 2.6 percent, to 7.24
liras, leading gains by index points in the benchmark  stock
index . Traders are betting the central bank will move to reverse
an increase in  reserve requirements , according to Mine Yoruk, a
trader at Erste Securities in Istanbul. The banking index
climbed 2.1 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Benjamin Harvey in Istanbul at 
